commitResults.messageBody: Add aboutme for Nicholas
Protect repo with CODEOWNERS file
Add Command Parser feature

All of WellNus' supported commands shall inherit from
  Command.class and implement shared behaviour.

This ensures that other classes such as WellNus can
  rely on the fact that all commands will support
  fundamental functionality such as execute().

While Command.class doesn't specify an isValidCommand()
  implementation, all child classes of Command must
  provide it so that other classes can use the corresponding
  isValidCommand() implementation to check whether a set of
  arguments belong to a specific feature/command.

Make this expectation clear by adding an explanation
  of this requirement to Command's class-level documentation.

In the unlikely case that null is passed as arguments
  to any Command's constructor, catch it immediately
  and throw a BadCommandException to prevent code
  from attempting to call methods on a null reference
  (dangerous).

commitResults.messageTitle: Check whether a feature is supported
commitResults.messageBody:
For now, give WellNus an isSupportedFeature implementation
  that can check whether a feature keyword is a recognised
  WellNus feature.

This allows Command child classes to check whether a given
  feature keyword is supported by WellNus.

Define a new HelpCommand.class that inherits from
  the new Command.class to support WellNus' 'help'
  command.

'help' allows users to learn about all the commands
  supported by WellNus, or even how to use a specific
  feature of WellNus.

Refer to our user guide for more information.

We throw an Exception when invalid arguments are presented
  to 'help'.

This is unideal as callers of HelpCommand cannot further
  distinguish what category of Exception occurred when
  HelpCommand fails.

Make use of the new BadCommandException from @nichyjt
  when we encounter invalid input arguments in HelpCommand.class

We can then be more specific about the type of Exception we
  throw in HelpCommand's constructor so that other classes
  can understand the type of Exception that HelpCommand
  encountered.
Add UI class for input and output
Fix AboutUs picture rendering bug

Enhancements are meant to be for changes to existing
  implementations, while features are meant to be new
  additions to WellNus.

Deserves to be its own separate category.

Enhancements are now its separate issue category,
  so remove it from the features issue template.
Add update command for atomic habits

Constructor parameters are passed by code in our own
  application, so we really should expect better.

Make this clear by using an assertion instead of a
  regular BadCommandException(implies that the user is
  at fault not us).

Invalid commands can be handled by the feature
  Manager directly, so there's no need for a
  separate class just to print a simple message.

We still use the seedu.duke package.

However we've already decided to brand our
  project WellNus, so update the package and
  our classes accordingly.
Refactor out validateCommand to Command

runEventDriver() will have to process commands,
  which might be invalid and throw BadCommandException.

Make this clear by marking runEventDriver() with
  the appropriate throws tag.

Abstract out the WellNus logo into a private static method
  so its more maintainable but just as elegant.

We have our own class for handling the printing of
  messages on the user's screen, so pass the greeting
  message to be printed by WellNus.main() to TextUi.class.

Apply SLAP and abstract out distinct sections of
  WellNus' logic into separate methods.

Now our WellNus.class is readable and neat.

Stop calling ourselves Duke in JavaDoc comments
  for WellNus.main().

Also, write proper documentation for WellNus.main().

Implement basic logic for reading and running user commands
  in WellNus.class.

Also, give a simple goodbye message to the user on exit via
  WellNus.byeUser().

Arrange methods alphabetically and by access
  modifier in WellNus.class.

commitResults.messageTitle: Define a Manager for the entire app
commitResults.messageBody:
MainMaager.class will be responsible for managing the
  basic commands like 'help' and delegating feature-specific
  commands to the corresponding feature's Manager.

Tell the user what to do after printing the WellNUS++ logo
  (i.e. enter a command or try 'help') so the app is less
  confusing when first initialised.

Duke.class is now WellNus.class, so rename its test class
  as well. Missed this earlier.

Abstract out logic for executing user's commands
  from MainManager.runEventDriver() into its own
  method to match the level of abstraction of
  this.greet().

@nichyjt removed some unnecessary methods from Manager.class,
  and those are meant to be implemented in MainManager only.

So implement these critical methods are private helper methods
  and refactor MainManager.executeCommands() accordingly.

WellNus crashes when an invalid command is given by
  the user.

This is not intended behaviour and it's not a critical
  exception, and the application can continue just fine.

Rewrite exception handling in MainManager.class so
  WellNus continues reading user commands even after
  an invalid command is issued.

MainManager.isSupportedFeature() allows other classes to check
  whether a feature is supported.

Now that MainManager.class is properly implemented,

  printing help messages.

Also update the methods provided by HelpCommand.class
  using the latest Command interface template.

Expose COMMAND_KEYWORD attribute of HelpCommand

Provide a very basic brief description of HelpCommand.

HelpCommand is supposed to support a basic form
  with no feature keyword, so we need to check that

  before we check whether it's supported feature.

Provide a very basic implementation of the main 'exit'
  command of WellNUS++.

Support basic commands and features now using a very
  abstract way of parsing commands and delegating to
  to correct feature Manager.

Change atomic habit's 'hb update' command syntax
  to allow easier testing and also standardise
  command syntax/user interaction.

Update AtomicHabitTest to test the new
  'hb update' command syntax and finally
  resolve the issues with the update
  command tests failing.

Wrongly required the feature keyword 'hb'
  in front of all commands given in atomic
  habits' Manager interface.

Remove this requirement so it matches behaviour
  in other features, as users would expect.

Atomic habit commands changed in the previous commits,
  update AtomicHabitTest to pass the new command
  syntax.

Add ReflectionManager.class as a supported feature
  Manager under MainManager.setSupportedFeatureManagers().

This allows all 'reflect' commands to work.

getFeatureName() is meant to be the feature keyword,
  i.e. 'hb' for atomic habits and 'reflect' for
  self reflection that you give to MainManager
  to open the corresponding feature Manager's
  event driver.

Might wanna consider renaming the method in
  Command.class @nichyjt?

commitResults.messageTitle: Add assertion to check for unintended behaviour
commitResults.messageBody:
I have my reservations about how SelfReflection.class
  stores its state, but this warrants team discussion.

For now, provide additional context in case of unintended
  usage of SelfReflection.getQuestions() that may cause
  crashes to help in case of related bugs/crashes.

MainManager parses the user command to check whether
  it's 'help' or 'exit' even when it's known to be
  a feature keyword(e.g. 'hb'), and this expectedly
  leads to a BadCommandException being thrown by
  MainManager.getMainCommandFor(), and consequently
  an ugly invalid command message.

Check that we didn't just pass control to a feature's
  Manager before trying to parse a main command to
  eliminate the ugly invalid command message.
Add atomic habits logo and additional assertions

commitResults.messageTitle: Revert "Add assertion to check for unintended behaviour"
commitResults.messageBody:
While the assertion prevents unintended SelfReflection.getQuestions()
  calls, it breaks intended SelfReflection.clearQuestions() behaviour,
  which cascades to the JUnit tests.

Not sure if there's a non-regression way of achieving this, but until
  then roll this change back, don't support code-breaking changes!

This reverts commit 454706ffa77904f3a574e393f56c12416fece4d0.
